</li>
<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="li-comment-43538">
<article id="comment-43538" class="comment">
<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/323e2c88a932a49dd09ab5501213f25a?s=44&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/323e2c88a932a49dd09ab5501213f25a?s=88&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' loading='lazy' decoding='async' /><cite><b class="fn">J Hayes</b> </cite><a href="https://allaboutcats.com/worlds-best-cat-litter-review#comment-43538"><time datetime="2020-11-02T12:52:50+00:00">Nov 2, 2020 at 12:52 pm</time></a> </header>
<section class="comment-content comment">
<p>I have used this intermittently over the years with Oka Cats Best but this year have only used World&#8217;s Best. The litter trays for both cats are kept in a bathroom but, unbeknown to me, corn when it becomes damp and moist develops a toxic mould and one cat had a severe allergic reaction which resulted in an asthma attack and a very poorly cat. The skin in between his toes was very red and the vet took lots of tests. A warning should be added to the packet about the potential dangers of corn based cat litter and how it should be properly stored and used. If you google it there are many comments on the internet re. concerns about corn based cat litter.</p>
</section>
<div class="reply">
<a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-43538' data-commentid="43538" data-postid="10110" data-belowelement="comment-43538" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to J Hayes" aria-label='Reply to J Hayes'>Reply</a> <span>&darr;</span> </div>
